diagnoses.name: Acute lymphocytic leukemia (ALL)
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer of the blood and bone marrow that affects white blood cells. Symptoms can include lymphadenopathy, leukocytosis, and systemic manifestations like fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Infectious mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: Often caused by the Epstein-Barr virus, it presents with symptoms such as fever, sore throat, swollen lymph glands, and in some cases, hepatosplenomegaly and leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Acute myeloid leukemia (AML)
diagnoses.description: A cancer of the blood and bone marrow characterized by an increase in white blood cells. Symptoms include fatigue, fever, infections, and signs like leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that attacks the glands that provide lubrication to the mouth and eyes. Symptoms can include dry mouth, cracking lips, and systemic effects such as lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki disease
diagnoses.description: A condition that causes inflammation in the walls of some blood vessels in the body. Symptoms include fever, swollen lymph nodes, cracked lips, and edema.

diagnoses.name: Chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL)
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer of the blood and bone marrow that progresses slowly. It is characterized by a high number of lymphocytes, with potential symptoms including lymphadenopathy and infections due to leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune disease that can affect any part of the body. Symptoms range widely but can include leukocytosis, lymphadenopathy, and renal involvement leading to pyuria.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, serious disorder of the skin and mucous membranes. It's often a reaction to a medication or an infection. Symptoms may include fever, sore throat, fatigue, lip swelling, and cracking.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic fever
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that can develop as a complication of untreated or poorly treated strep throat. Symptoms include fever, painful and tender joints, and in some cases, a red lattice-like rash.

diagnoses.name: Hodgkin's lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A cancer of the lymphatic system which is part of the immune system. Symptoms include painless swelling of lymph nodes in the neck, armpits, or groin, fatigue, and night sweats.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki Disease
diagnoses.description: Kawasaki disease is a rare condition that mainly affects children under the age of 5. It's characterized by inflammation of blood vessels throughout the body and can lead to coronary artery aneurysms. Key features include fever, rash, swelling of the hands and feet, redness in the eyes, lips, and throat, along with the symptoms you've described.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet Fever
diagnoses.description: Scarlet fever is an illness that can occur as a result of a group A Streptococcus (group A strep) infection. The disease may affect the skin and mucous membranes, showing symptoms including a bright red rash on the body, sore throat, fever, and the 'strawberry' tongue indicative of your listed symptom.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: Infectious mononucleosis, also known as mono, is usually caused by the Epstein-Barr virus. Symptoms can include fatigue, fever, inflamed throat, swollen lymph nodes in the neck, enlarged spleen, swollen liver, and, in some cases, the characteristics you mentioned.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Shock Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Toxic Shock Syndrome (TSS) is a rare, life-threatening complication of certain types of bacterial infections. Often associated with tampon use, TSS can also arise from skin wounds and surgery. Symptoms include high fever, rash, skin peeling, and organ damage.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE) is an autoimmune disease in which the immune system attacks its own tissues, causing widespread inflammation and tissue damage in the affected organs. It can manifest in many ways, including dermatologic symptoms, joint pain, and more severe effects like kidney dysfunction.

diagnoses.name: Acute Leukemia
diagnoses.description: Acute leukemia is a type of cancer of the blood and bone marrow with excess immature white blood cells. It presents rapidly and aggressively and can lead to symptoms like bruising, fatigue, fever, and an increased risk of infections, along with symptoms you've mentioned as the disease progresses.

diagnoses.name: Drug Reaction with Eosinophilia and Systemic Symptoms (DRESS) syndrome
diagnoses.description: DRESS syndrome is a severe skin reaction that includes swelling, rashes, and fever, along with involvement of the liver, kidneys, lungs, heart, and pancreas. It's a reaction to a medication up to three months after starting the drug.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Stevens-Johnson Syndrome (SJS) is a rare, serious disorder of your skin and mucous membranes. It's usually a reaction to a medication or an infection. SJS causes your skin to blister and peel, leading to painful rashes that spread and coalesce.

diagnoses.name: Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis
diagnoses.description: Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis (JIA) encompasses all forms of arthritis that begin before the age of 16, persist for more than six weeks, and are of unknown cause. It can cause lymphadenopathy, fever, rash, and organ inflammation in addition to joint symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schönlein Purpura
diagnoses.description: Henoch-Schönlein purpura (HSP) is a disease involving inflammation of small blood vessels. It typically results in a rash, joint pain, gastrointestinal symptoms, and nephritis. The rash may look like small bruises or reddish-purple spots, mostly on legs and buttocks.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect multiple systems including the kidneys (nephritis), joints (arthropathy), and heart (acute pericarditis). Skin manifestations often present as a rash, which might be described as erythematous-violaceous.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic Fever
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that can develop as a complication of untreated or poorly treated strep throat from group A streptococcus. Can affect the heart, joints, skin, and brain. Rheumatic fever may cause acute pericarditis and migratory arthropathy.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder presenting symptoms of multiple autoimmune diseases, including systemic lupus erythematosus, scleroderma, and polymyositis. Symptoms may include arthropathy, acute pericarditis, and renal involvement.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease affecting multiple organs in the body, primarily the lungs and lymph glands. Skin rashes and lesions (erythematous-violaceous nodules), joint inflammation (arthropathy), and cardiac involvement (acute pericarditis) can be seen.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: A rare inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and a distinctive skin rash. It might be associated with inflammatory conditions affecting other organs, including the joints and heart.

diagnoses.name: Viral Myocarditis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the heart muscle, often caused by a viral infection. Although primarily affecting the heart, systemic viral infections can also lead to symptoms similar to acute pericarditis, joint involvement, and kidney issues.

diagnoses.name: Psoriatic Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory arthritis associated with psoriasis, characterized by joint pain and swelling. Patients may also present with erythematous-violaceous plaques typical of psoriasis and can occasionally have cardiac involvement.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: Infectious disease caused by Borrelia burgdorferi bacteria, transmitted via ticks. It can cause a variety of symptoms, potentially including erythematous-violaceous skin manifestations, arthralgia or arthritis, and, in rare cases, carditis resembling acute pericarditis.

diagnoses.name: Post-streptococcal Glomerulonephritis
diagnoses.description: A kidney disease that occurs after infection with certain strains of streptococcus bacteria. While primarily affecting the kidneys, it can have systemic effects, including joint pain and potentially cardiac involvement.

diagnoses.name: Drug-induced Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A lupus-like syndrome caused by certain prescription drugs. Symptoms mimic those of systemic lupus erythematosus, including joint pain, heart inflammation, and possible skin rashes.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can affect the nervous system, causing seizures, and the hematologic system, leading to thrombocytopenia and autoimmune hemolysis. Fever and delirium can also be presenting symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Evans Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Evans Syndrome is a rare autoimmune disorder characterized by the combination of autoimmune hemolytic anemia and thrombocytopenia, which could be associated with fever and neurological symptoms like seizures and delirium.

diagnoses.name: Antiphospholipid Syndrome (APS)
diagnoses.rationale: APS can lead to thrombocytopenia and is associated with neurological manifestations including seizures. Hemolytic anemia and fever are also seen in this context.

diagnoses.name: Thrombotic Thrombocytopenic Purpura (TTP)
diagnoses.rationale: TTP is characterized by thrombocytopenia and hemolytic anemia. It can involve fever and neurological findings, such as seizures and mental status changes.

diagnoses.name: Hemophagocytic Lymphohistiocytosis (HLH)
diagnoses.rationale: HLH is an aggressive, life-threatening syndrome of excessive immune activation. It presents with fever, hemophagocytosis, and can cause neurological symptoms, thrombocytopenia, and hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.rationale: In some severe cases, infectious mononucleosis can present with hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia, fever, and neurological complications such as seizures.

diagnoses.name: Malaria
diagnoses.rationale: Malaria can cause fever, neurological symptoms such as seizures, thrombocytopenia, and hemolytic anemia in severe cases.

diagnoses.name: Septicemia
diagnoses.rationale: Severe infections or septicemia can lead to a wide array of hematologic abnormalities, including thrombocytopenia and hemolytic anemia, fever, delirium, and seizures as part of sepsis-associated encephalopathy.

diagnoses.name: Disseminated Intravascular Coagulation (DIC)
diagnoses.rationale: DIC can present with thrombocytopenia and hemolytic anemia, fever, seizures, and altered mental status as part of a severe underlying condition, often with an infectious trigger.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.rationale: In its late stages, Lyme Disease can cause neurological disorders (including seizures and delirium), fever, and, though less commonly, hematological changes such as thrombocytopenia and autoimmune hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disease can explain the presence of atrophic scarring (skin involvement), pleural effusion (lung involvement), delirium (neuropsychiatric involvement), nephritis (kidney involvement), and proteinuria (a sign of kidney disease).

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: Vasculitis can involve multiple organ systems, potentially leading to nephritis (especially in cases like Microscopic Polyangiitis or Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis), skin changes (including atrophic scarring), pleural effusions, along with nervous system involvement that can manifest as delirium.

diagnoses.name: Goodpasture’s Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune condition is characterized by the presence of nephritis and lung hemorrhage, which can lead to pleural effusion. While less directly associated with atrophic scarring and delirium, its severe impact on lung and renal function can contribute to these conditions as secondary effects.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD)
diagnoses.rationale: CKD can lead to proteinuria due to long-standing kidney damage. Uremic syndrome related to severe CKD can cause fluid accumulation including pleural effusion and contribute to neurological conditions like delirium.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.rationale: Sarcoidosis is a granulomatous disease that might involve the skin causing atrophic scarring, the kidneys leading to nephritis, and the lungs resulting in pleural effusion. Neurosarcoidosis, though less common, can manifest with symptoms such as delirium.

diagnoses.name: Infective Endocarditis
diagnoses.rationale: While not a classic presentation, infective endocarditis can present with renal complications like nephritis and proteinuria due to emboli or immune complex deposition. Heart failure secondary to endocarditis can cause pleural effusion. Delirium can occur due to a variety of factors including systemic infection and embolic strokes.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.rationale: Certain types of lymphoma could cause nephritis and proteinuria through direct invasion or paraneoplastic syndrome. They can also cause pleural effusion either by lymphatic obstruction or direct involvement. Central nervous system (CNS) lymphoma or paraneoplastic syndromes might lead to delirium. Skin involvement can be less common but possible.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.rationale: TB can cause pleural effusion and renal involvement leading to nephritis and proteinuria. Central nervous system involvement can cause delirium, and skin tuberculosis can present with atrophic scarring.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.rationale: Advanced HIV/AIDS can lead to nephropathy (resulting in proteinuria and potentially nephritis), CNS involvement (potentially causing delirium), and a variety of skin conditions including atrophic scars. Pleural effusion can occur secondary to opportunistic infections.

diagnoses.name: Schistosomiasis
diagnoses.rationale: This parasitic disease can cause nephritis and proteinuria due to immune complex deposition. Pleural effusion can result from pulmonary involvement. Atrophic scarring can occur as a result of the chronic skin lesions. CNS involvement, including delirium, can occur but is rare.

diagnoses: Vitamin Deficiencies – Certain vitamin deficiencies (like B12 or folate) could theoretically cause a combination of symptoms like dysosmia (altered sense of smell), oral pain, and possibly lead to gothic symptoms like hyperactivity. Monocytosis could also be related as a manifestation of an underlying hematologic abnormality due to deficiency.

Chronic Stress or Anxiety – Chronic stress or anxiety can lead to hyperactivity, alterations in skin condition such as dyshidrotic eczema, and indirectly affect oral health causing oral pain. Neurological and psychological impacts of stress might also contribute to symptoms like dysosmia.

Sjögren’s Syndrome – This is an autoimmune disease that primarily affects moisture-producing glands, leading to symptoms such as dry mouth (which could be perceived as oral pain), and could also potentially contribute to systemic manifestations that indirectly cause or exacerbate other reported symptoms.

Iron Deficiency Anemia – Aside from its classic symptoms, severe iron deficiency can contribute to oral pain (due to atrophic changes in the oral mucosa), and possibly dyshidrotic eczema. Altered taste or smell (dysosmia) and hyperactivity or restlessness (especially in children) might also be observed in some cases.

Behçet's Disease – This rare disorder causes blood vessel inflammation throughout your body. Oral pain (due to mouth ulcers), skin manifestations like eczema, and systemic symptoms such as those affecting the nervous system (potentially hyperactivity) could occur. Monocytosis might be observed as an inflammatory response.

Hypothyroidism – Altered metabolism in hypothyroidism can lead to various nonspecific symptoms including changes in skin condition like dyshidrotic eczema, and potentially oral health issues. It can sometimes manifest with psychiatric or neurological symptoms (like hyperactivity or altered senses) due to its systemic nature.

Zinc Deficiency – Zinc is crucial for immune function, skin health, and wound healing. A deficiency can lead to symptoms like dyshidrotic eczema, altered taste or smell (dysosmia), and indirectly lead to oral health issues. It could potentially contribute to hyperactivity or attention issues due to its role in neurological function.

Allergic Reactions or Atopic Dermatitis – Allergies can directly cause skin conditions such as dyshidrotic eczema and indirectly cause issues like oral pain (from associated conditions like eosinophilic esophagitis). Hyperactivity can sometimes be observed in allergic reactions, particularly in children.

Multiple Sclerosis (MS) – While MS is primarily a neurological condition, it can present with a wide variety of symptoms including dysosmia, oral pain (from neuralgia), and potentially lead to skin issues like eczema due to autonomic dysregulation. Hyperactivity or restlessness might be part of the broader neurological impact.

Psychogenic Disorders – In some cases, a combination of symptoms like oral pain, hyperactivity, dysosmia, and dermatological issues like dyshidrotic eczema could be manifestations of underlying psychogenic or somatoform disorders, particularly in the absence of clear organic causes.

diagnoses.name: Hypereosinophilic Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by a persistently high eosinophil count in the blood for no identifiable reason and associated with organ damage. Symptoms may include weakness, fever, cough, and in some cases, poor healing and lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Churg-Strauss Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Also known as eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis, it is a small vessel vasculitis associated with asthma and eosinophilia. Symptoms can include allergic rhinitis, sinusitis, and skin abnormalities.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that begins in the lymphatic system. It can cause lymphadenopathy, eosinophilia, and sometimes poor healing due to the impact on the immune system.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can affect many parts of the body including skin, joints, kidneys, and the nervous system. Symptoms can be quite varied but may include lymphadenopathy and poor healing.

diagnoses.name: Drug Reaction with Eosinophilia and Systemic Symptoms (DRESS) Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A severe adverse drug reaction characterized by rash, hematologic abnormalities like eosinophilia, and internal organ involvement. Patients may also complain of general malaise and lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Parasitic Infections
diagnoses.description: Parasites like schistosomiasis, strongyloidiasis, and filariasis can cause eosinophilia and lymphadenopathy. Symptoms can vary widely depending on the parasite but can include poor healing and edema.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Contact Dermatitis
diagnoses.description: A skin reaction following contact with a substance or allergen that the immune system recognizes as foreign. This can occasionally lead to secondary infection and poor healing if the barrier of the skin is compromised.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that affects multiple organs in the body, but mostly the lungs and lymph glands. Characterized by the formation of granulomas, it can cause lymphadenopathy and, though less commonly, eosinophilia.

diagnoses.name: Kimura Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare chronic inflammatory disorder that involves subcutaneous nodules, predominantly in the head and neck region, eosinophilia, and lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition. Although not directly associated with eosinophilia or lymphadenitis, patients may report chemical sensitivities and fluctuating symptoms including poor healing.

diagnoses.name: Pheochromocytoma
diagnoses.description: A rare tumor of adrenal gland tissue. It results in the release of too much epinephrine and norepinephrine, hormones that control heart rate, metabolism, and blood pressure.

diagnoses.name: Hyperthyroidism
diagnoses.description: Overproduction of a hormone by the butterfly-shaped gland in the neck (thyroid). Can cause unexpected weight loss, rapid or irregular heartbeat, sweating, and nervousness or irritability.

diagnoses.name: Generalized Anxiety Disorder (GAD)
diagnoses.description: An anxiety disorder characterized by chronic anxiety, exaggerated worry, and tension, even when there is little or nothing to provoke it.

diagnoses.name: Urinary Tract Infection (UTI)
diagnoses.description: An infection in any part of the urinary system, including kidneys, bladder, ureters, and urethra. Most infections involve the lower urinary tract — the bladder and the urethra.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD)
diagnoses.description: The gradual loss of kidney function over time. Can lead to high blood pressure, anemia, weak bones, poor nutritional health and nerve damage. Also, kidney disease increases your risk of having heart and blood vessel disease.

diagnoses.name: Mastocytosis
diagnoses.description: A disorder that results in the excessive accumulation of mast cells in the skin and/or internal organs. Dermatographism, which is a severe skin irritation, is one symptom.

diagnoses.name: Autonomic Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A group of symptoms that occur when there is damage to the nerves that manage every day body functions such as blood pressure, heart rate, bowel and bladder emptying, and digestion.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. MS can cause a variety of symptoms, including vision loss, pain, fatigue, and impaired coordination.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A group of diseases that result in too much sugar in the blood (high blood glucose). Diabetes can cause damage to the nerves throughout your body, leading to various symptoms including issues with blood pressure regulation.

diagnoses.name: Hypoglycemia
diagnoses.description: A condition caused by a very low level of blood sugar (glucose), your body's main energy source. Hypoglycemia can cause anxiety, vision problems and confusion.

diagnoses.name: Common Variable Immune Deficiency (CVID)
diagnoses.description: CVID is a disorder characterized by low levels of several immunoglobulin classes, leading to an increased susceptibility to infections. Patients may also exhibit malabsorption syndromes, autoimmune manifestations, and an increased risk of malignancies.

diagnoses.name: Selective Immunoglobulin A Deficiency
diagnoses.description: This condition involves low or absent levels of Immunoglobulin A (IgA) in the presence of normal levels of other immunoglobulins. It may present with malabsorption, autoimmune diseases, and recurrent infections.

diagnoses.name: Gastrointestinal Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions such as Crohn's disease or celiac disease can lead to malabsorption and nutritional deficiencies, which can cause a wide range of symptoms including angioedema and xerosis due to vitamin and mineral deficiencies.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that attacks the glands that provide lubrication to the eyes and mouth. It can lead to xerosis and is associated with various immunological abnormalities including low immunoglobulin levels.

diagnoses.name: Primary Biliary Cirrhosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic disease that slowly destroys the bile ducts within the liver, leading to malabsorption of fats and fat-soluble vitamins, which can contribute to xerosis and other systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by insufficient thyroid hormone production, can lead to depression, dry skin (xerosis), and can affect the immune system, albeit less commonly decreasing immunoglobulins.

diagnoses.name: Depression with Somatic Symptoms
diagnoses.description: Depression can manifest with various somatic symptoms including decreased immune function. Proper diagnosis of depression and associated physical complaints is crucial for effective treatment.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare, genetic disorder caused by low levels or improper function of a protein called C1 inhibitor, affecting the immune system and leading to episodes of angioedema.

diagnoses.name: Nutritional Deficiencies
diagnoses.description: Deficits in essential vitamins and minerals due to malabsorption can lead to a wide range of symptoms including depression, weakened immune response, and skin conditions such as xerosis.

diagnoses.name: Atopic Dermatitis
diagnoses.description: A chronic skin condition that can cause xerosis and is associated with immune dysfunction, although it is less commonly linked to decreased immunoglobulins or the other symptoms listed here.

diagnoses.reasoning: While not a direct match for all symptoms, lung cancer can manifest with pneumonia and bronchitis symptoms due to lung involvement. However, it doesn't directly cause migratory patchy macular erythema, hypoferritinemia, or interstitial cystitis.

diagnoses.name: Connective Tissue Diseases
diagnoses.reasoning: Connective tissue diseases, such as lupus or dermatomyositis, can lead to skin manifestations (migratory patchy macular erythema), lung involvement (pneumonia, bronchitis), though they do not typically cause hypoferritinemia or interstitial cystitis directly.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Diseases (e.g., TB, HIV)

Blepharospasm may indicate conditions affecting neurological function or muscle control.

Fatigue, a common symptom, can be associated with a wide range of conditions from mild to severe, including viral infections, chronic fatigue syndrome, depression, or metabolic disorders like diabetes.
Dyspepsia, often related to gastrointestinal issues, could point towards conditions like gastritis, GERD, or peptic ulcers.
Glycemic lability, implying fluctuations in blood sugar levels, could suggest diabetes mellitus, insulinoma, or issues with medication management in known diabetic patients.
Sinusitis, indicating inflammation of the sinuses, could be related to infections (viral, bacterial, or fungal), allergic rhinitis, or structural issues in the nasal passages.
Blepharospasm combined with fatigue and dyspepsia might suggest an underlying systemic condition, such as an autoimmune disorder or Parkinson's disease.
The combination of glycemic lability and fatigue could be indicative of endocrine disorders, particularly those involving the pancreas or adrenal glands.
Chronic sinusitis, in combination with systemic symptoms like fatigue and dyspepsia, might suggest an underlying immunodeficiency or chronic inflammatory condition like sarcoidosis.
When considering blepharospasm alongside systemic symptoms such as fatigue, one must also consider neurological conditions like multiple sclerosis or essential tremor.
The collection of these symptoms could also indicate side effects from certain medications, necessitating a thorough medication review.

diagnoses.description: A condition that makes your skin red and itchy (pruritis). It's common in children but can occur at any age. It may be associated with other allergic conditions like asthma or hay fever.

diagnoses.description: Commonly known as the common cold, it can cause rhinorrhea, wheezing (especially in asthmatic patients), and conjunctival injections.

diagnoses.name: Acute Sinusitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the sinuses, often caused by infection. Symptoms can include rhinorrhea, facial pain, and sometimes wheezing if the sinusitis leads to a secondary chest infection.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.description: A chronic digestive disease where stomach acid or, occasionally, stomach content, flows back into your esophagus, which might lead to vomiting and, in chronic cases, could aggravate asthma symptoms causing wheezing.

diagnoses.name: Conjunctivitis
diagnoses.description: Also known as pink eye, it is inflammation or infection of the outer membrane of the eyeball and the inner eyelid (conjunctival injections).

diagnoses.name: Extrinsic Allergic Alveolitis
diagnoses.description: Also known as hypersensitivity pneumonitis, it's an allergic lung disease resulting from inhalation of dusts, molds, and chemicals, leading to symptoms such as wheezing and, occasionally, systemic symptoms like vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.details: Migraine headaches can cause severe throbbing pain or a pulsing sensation, usually on one side of the head. It's often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and extreme sensitivity to light and sound. Migraine attacks can cause significant pain for hours to days and can be so severe that the pain is disabling.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.details: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). The immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers, causing communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body. Symptoms include numbness, weakness, and problems with coordination and balance.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.details: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. A stroke is a medical emergency, and prompt treatment is crucial. Symptoms can include trouble speaking and understanding what others are saying, paralysis or numbness of the face, arm or leg, and headache.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Neuropathy
diagnoses.details: Diabetic neuropathy is a type of nerve damage that can occur if you have diabetes. High blood sugar (glucose) can injure nerves throughout your body. Diabetic neuropathy most often damages nerves in your legs and feet. Symptoms can include numbness, reduced ability to feel pain or temperature changes, and muscle weakness.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.details: A brain tumor is a mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Some are benign (noncancerous), and some are malignant (cancerous). Symptoms can include headaches (often worse in the morning), weakness, numbness, and changes in speech or vision.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.details: Anemia is a condition in which you lack enough healthy red blood cells to carry adequate oxygen to your body's tissues. Having anemia may make you feel tired and weak. Severe or long-lasting anemia can cause damage to your heart, brain, and other organs in your body. Some forms of anemia can be serious or even fatal if not diagnosed and treated.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.details: Lyme disease is caused by four main species of bacteria. Lyme disease is transmitted by the bite of an infected black-legged tick, commonly known as a deer tick. Symptoms can include headache, fatigue, fever, and a skin rash called erythema migrans. If left untreated, infection can spread to joints, the heart, and the nervous system.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.details: Meningitis is an inflammation of the fluid and membranes (meninges) surrounding your brain and spinal cord. The swelling from meningitis typically triggers symptoms such as headache, fever, and a stiff neck. It can be life-threatening and requires urgent antibiotic treatment.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.details: Hypothyroidism, also called underactive thyroid, is a condition in which your thyroid gland doesn't produce enough of certain crucial hormones. Hypothyroidism may not cause noticeable symptoms in the early stages. Over time, untreated hypothyroidism can cause a number of health problems, such as obesity, joint pain, infertility, and heart disease. Symptoms include fatigue, increased sensitivity to cold, and muscle weakness.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.details: Chronic fatigue syndrome (CFS) is a complicated disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition. The fatigue may worsen with physical or mental activity, but doesn't improve with rest. It can be severely debilitating and affect daily activities.

diagnoses.description: Brain tumors can press on nerve tissues and cause symptoms such as headaches, speech or language difficulties, weakness on one side of the body, and sometimes visual disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a TIA is a brief period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke, such as speech impairment and weakness. Unlike a stroke, the symptoms of a TIA are temporary and usually resolve within 24 hours.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: Epilepsy is a neurological disorder marked by sudden recurrent episodes of sensory disturbance, loss of consciousness, or convulsions. It can manifest as speech disturbances, sensory illusions such as scintillations, weakness, and headache post-seizure.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. Symptoms can include fatigue, speech disturbance, weakness, and neurological symptoms, including visual disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A brain abscess is a collection of pus that develops in response to an infection or trauma. Symptoms can include headache, neurologic deficits like aphasia and weakness, and sometimes visual problems depending on the location of the abscess.

diagnoses.name: Intracerebral Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: This occurs when a diseased blood vessel within the brain bursts, allowing blood to leak inside the brain. Symptoms can include sudden headache, weakness, aphasia, and altered vision.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Encephalitis is inflammation of the brain. Viruses are the most common cause of encephalitis. Symptoms include headache, weakness, fever, seizures, and cognitive deficits like aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: Meningitis is inflammation of the fluid and membranes surrounding your brain and spinal cord. Symptoms can include headache, fever, stiffness, and in severe cases, symptoms like aphasia and weakness due to brain involvement.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition characterized by intense headaches often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Tension Headache
diagnoses.description: A common type of headache characterized by persistent dull pain, typically on both sides of the head, often associated with muscle tightness in the neck or scalp.

diagnoses.name: Cluster Headache
diagnoses.description: Rare but extremely painful headaches occurring in clusters, often around one eye, with possible redness, tearing, and nasal congestion.

diagnoses.name: Subarachnoid Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: Bleeding in the space between the brain and the tissue covering the brain, often presenting with a sudden, severe headache.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the membranes (meninges) surrounding the brain and spinal cord, characterized by headache, fever, and stiff neck.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the brain often caused by a viral infection, leading to flu-like symptoms including headache, fever, confusion, and sometimes seizures or sensory issues.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Abnormal cell growth within the brain, which can cause headaches, seizures, and other neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Glaucoma
diagnoses.description: A group of eye conditions that damage the optic nerve, often causing pain, headache, and visual disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease of the central nervous system leading to fatigue, weakness, visual disturbances, and coordination issues.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.description: A condition marked by a deficiency of red blood cells or hemoglobin in the blood, leading to fatigue, weakness, and sometimes headache.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.reason: SLE can manifest with a wide range of symptoms including discoid rash and pericardial effusion. Lupus can also affect the nervous system, potentially causing cranial neuropathy.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.reason: This condition is known for causing a distinctive skin rash (which can resemble discoid rash) and muscle weakness. Cardiac involvement could hypothetically manifest as pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.reason: MCTD presents with features of several autoimmune diseases including SLE, and can show symptoms such as pericardial effusion and neurologic manifestations that might resemble cranial neuropathy.

diagnoses.name: Scleroderma
diagnoses.reason: Scleroderma can cause telangiectasias and may have cardiac involvement including pericardial effusion. Scleroderma can also affect the skin in ways that might be misinterpreted as discoid rash.

diagnoses.name: Primary Biliary Cirrhosis
diagnoses.reason: Although primarily a liver disease, it can present with telangiectasias. Some associated autoimmune features can overlap with symptoms such as those mentioned.

diagnoses.name: Lichen Planus
diagnoses.reason: Given as a symptom, but when chronic and systemic, it can be associated with various systemic manifestations.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's syndrome
diagnoses.reason: It is associated with a wide range of symptoms including neurological involvement that could potentially cover cranial neuropathy.

diagnoses.name: Eosinophilic Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis (Churg-Strauss Syndrome)
diagnoses.reason: This vasculitis can cause a variety of dermatologic manifestations, potentially similar to discoid rash, and has been associated with neuropathy. Cardiac involvement can lead to pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis (Wegener's)
diagnoses.reason: Another type of vasculitis that could theoretically present with a range of symptoms due to its systemic nature, potentially including neuropathies and skin manifestations.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.reason: Although primarily known for affecting the joints, RA can have systemic manifestations including rheumatoid nodules that might be confused with discoid rash and cardiovascular complications such as pericardial effusion.
